05769nam a22007455i 9780824838416DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20142014hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1029814865  a(OCoLC)1032685035  a(OCoLC)1037933215  a(OCoLC)1041919856  a(OCoLC)1045546017  a97808248384167 a10.1515/97808248384162doi  a(DE-B1597)483857  a(OCoLC)1024037900  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aPL832.A52b.Z663 2014eb 7aLIT0080302bisacsh04a895.6/3442231 aDodd, Stephen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Youth of Things :bLife and Death in the Age of Kajii Motojiro /cStephen Dodd. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Illness as Empowerment -- t2. Modernism and Its Endings -- t3. Things of Beauty -- t4. The Subject of Change -- tTranslations -- tLemon -- tMire -- tOn the Road -- tThe Past -- tAfter the Snow -- tLandscapes of the Heart -- tThe Ascension of K, or K’s Drowning -- tWinter Days -- tUnder the Cherry Trees -- tInstrumental Illusions -- tThe Story of the Bamboo Pipe -- tBlue Sky -- tWinter Flies -- tCertain Feelings on a Cliff Top -- tCaresses -- tScroll of Darkness -- tMating -- tThe Carefree Patient -- tPublication History -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen he died from tuberculosis at the age of thirty-one, Kajii Motojirō had written only twenty short stories. Yet his life and work, it is argued here, sheds light on a significant moment in Japanese history and, ultimately, adds to our understanding of how modern Japanese identity developed. By the time Kajii began to write in the mid-1920s there was heated debate among his peers over “legitimate” forms of literary expression: Japanese Romantics questioned the value of a western-inspired version of modernity; others were influenced by Marxist proletarian literature or modernist experimentation; still others tried to create a distinctly Japanese fictional style that concentrated on first-person perspective, the so-called “I-novel.” There was a general sense that Japan needed to reinvent itself, but writers and artists were at odds over what form this reinvention should take. Throughout his career, Kajii drew from these various camps but belonged to none of them, making his work an invaluable indicator of a culture in crisis and transition. The Youth of Things is the first full-length book devoted to Kajii Motojirō. It brings together English translations of nearly all his completed stories with an analysis of his literature in the context of several major themes that locate him in 1920s Japan. In particular, Dodd links the writer’s work with the physical body: Kajii’s subjective literary presence was grounded first and foremost in his TB-stricken physical body, hence one cannot be studied without the other. His concerns with health and mortality drove him to play a central role in constructing a language for modern literature and to offer new insights into ideas that intrigued so many other Taishō intellectuals and writers. In addition, Kajii’s early years as a writer were strongly influenced by the cosmopolitan humanism of the White Birch (Shirakaba) school, but by the time his final work was published in the early 1930s, an environment of greater cultural introspection was beginning to take root, encapsulated in the expression “return to Japan” (nihon kaiki). Only a few years separate these two moments in time, but they represent a profound shift in the aspirations and expectations of a whole generation of writers. Through a study of Kajii’s writing, this book offers some sense of the demise of one cultural moment and the creation of another.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aDeath in literature. 0aMortality in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Japanese.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2014-2016z978311056413640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082483841640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824838416423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824838416.jpg  a978-3-11-056413-6  UHP eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK